r:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/I01618X/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>This project builds on work undertaken as part of the ESRC-funded project &lt;em>Dispute Resolution and Avoidance in Special and Additional Support Needs in England and Scotland&lt;/em> (RES-062-23-0803). The original research assessed the success of alternative dispute resolution (ADR) as the means of settling disputes in the field of additional support needs (ASN). &lt;br />&lt;br />ADR involves negotiation between parties using mediators, and is believed to be less costly and stressful for all concerned than more formal methods of dispute resolution involving courts and tribunals. Despite the official promotion of ADR, our research found that it has not been extensively used. Most disagreements were dealt with through informal negotiation at school level, with only a minority of parents choosing to use a more formal dispute resolution route. Of those who did, the tribunal was often preferred to mediation because it appeared to provide enforceable recommendations. &lt;br />&lt;br />The purpose of this knowledge exchange project is to enhance parents? and practitioners? understanding of different types of dispute resolution, using think tanks to inform the production of a service framework guide.&amp;nbsp; &lt;br />&lt;br />&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2012-07-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2011-02-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>71852</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs><gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:description>Think tank 2 : how to use the tribunal constructively</gtr:description><gtr:form>Participation in an activity, workshop or similar</gtr:form><gtr:geographicReach>National</gtr:geographicReach><gtr:id>6F80E55A-099E-4895-954B-4EDD5FF50148</gtr:id><gtr:impact>This knowledge exchange project aims to:
1) consider what can be done to improve communication between parents of children with additional support needs and professionals
2) enhance understanding of different types of dispute resolution
3) identify how each dispute resolution process may be used more effectively

This is the second think tank in a series of three. It focuses on how to use the tribunal constructively, ensuring that decisions are made swiftly and that the process is as user friendly as possible. It also considers how advocacy can be used to support parents in accessing the tribunal.

What could be done to improve communication between parents of children with additional support needs and professionals were discussed, understanding of different types of dispute resolution was enhanced and ways in which each dispute resolution process might be used more effectively were identified.</gtr:impact><gtr:outcomeId>r-5292848772.6420612b3dab88</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:partOfOfficialScheme>false</gtr:partOfOfficialScheme><gtr:presentationType>keynote/invited speaker</gtr:presentationType><gtr:primaryAudience>Professional Practitioners</gtr:primaryAudience><gtr:url>http://www.ed.ac.uk/schools-departments/education/rke/centres-groups/creid/news-events/events-archive/events-archive-2011/think-tank-2</gtr:url><gtr:year>2011</gtr:year></gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:description>Think tank 1 : communicating effectively with parents of children with additional support needs</gtr:description><gtr:form>Participation in an activity, workshop or similar</gtr:form><gtr:geographicReach>National</gtr:geographicReach><gtr:id>F37B40DC-775D-40E2-943A-C52BD2B646F1</gtr:id><gtr:impact>This knowledge exchange project aims to:
1) consider what can be done to improve communication between parents of children with additional support needs and professionals
2) enhance understanding of different types of dispute resolution
3) identify how each dispute resolution process may be used more effectively

This is the first think tank in a series of three. It focuses on developing a better understanding of the communication difficulties which may arise and what can be done to build more productive working relationships between parents and professionals, using mediation where appropriate. Subsequent think tanks will consider how to use the tribunal constructively and how to engage children in ASN decision-making.

Better understanding of the communication difficulties which might arise was promoted; and things that could be done to build more productive working relationships between parents and professionals, using mediation where appropriate, were discussed.</gtr:impact><gtr:outcomeId>r-4332914831.42684652b43d6de</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:partOfOfficialScheme>false</gtr:partOfOfficialScheme><gtr:presentationType>keynote/invited speaker</gtr:presentationType><gtr:primaryAudience>Professional Practitioners</gtr:primaryAudience><gtr:url>http://www.ed.ac.uk/schools-departments/education/rke/centres-groups/creid/news-events/events-archive/events-archive-2011/think-tank-1</gtr:url><gtr:year>2011</gtr:year></gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:description>Dissemination event: Effective communication and dispute resolution in additional support needs</gtr:description><gtr:form>Participation in an activity, workshop or similar</gtr:form><gtr:geographicReach>National</gtr:geographicReach><gtr:id>11279A12-9FF0-4D3D-B3A6-5E976910AA43</gtr:id><gtr:impact>Following three think tanks, a final event was held in the Scottish Parliament on 23rd May 2012. The event attracted 80 people and was sponsored by Adam Ingram, MSP. The main speaker was Muriel Gray, author and broadcaster.

Findings from the research and the think tanks, including case studies, were discussed in a service framework guide &amp;quot;Communication Matters: Improving Communication in Additional Support Needs&amp;quot; (http://www.docs.hss.ed.ac.uk/education/creid/NewsEvents/40i_E)</gtr:impact><gtr:outcomeId>r-3749173342.94800952b680fb8</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:partOfOfficialScheme>false</gtr:partOfOfficialScheme><gtr:presentationType>keynote/invited speaker</gtr:presentationType><gtr:primaryAudience>Professional Practitioners</gtr:primaryAudience><gtr:url>http://www.ed.ac.uk/schools-departments/education/rke/centres-groups/creid/news-events/events-archive/events-archive-2012/esrc-improve-comm-in-asn</gtr:url><gtr:year>2012</gtr:year></gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:description>Think tank 3 : involving children and young people in ASN decision-making</gtr:description><gtr:form>Participation in an activity, workshop or similar</gtr:form><gtr:geographicReach>National</gtr:geographicReach><gtr:id>7BA75340-9D43-4972-AA8D-5AEBB183A6CC</gtr:id><gtr:impact>This is the third think tank in a series which has focused on avoiding disputes in additional support needs through better communication and dealing with disputes effectively when they arise. The questions addressed are the following: Why are children so little involved in ASN decision-making and dispute resolution procedures? Are efforts to enhance their involvement tokenistic and what would need to be done to make their involvement meaningful? How can we work effectively with children from different social backgrounds, of different ages and with different types of difficulty?

The following questions being addressed were discussed:
- Why are children so little involved in ASN decision-making and dispute resolution procedures? 
- Are efforts to enhance their involvement tokenistic and what would need to be done to make their involvement meaningful? 
